[{"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-07-05T18:00:00+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Illustration of a phone with a photo of a cat featured on-screen.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/wXNDjFDJLvSHAat7n8K3FQTJY1w=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73445697/HT015_S_Haddad_ios_iphone_14_04.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Illustration by Samar Haddad / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"42drXi\">It may sound funny to say this, but PDF files \u2014 electronic copies of printed documents \u2014 are still around and are still very useful. Short for Portable Document Format, PDFs allow you to create a digital version of a paper document, letting you store and access them a lot easier than having to rifle through a filing cabinet.</p>\n<p id=\"fYFVg9\">While there are a variety of PDF apps available \u2014 Adobe Acrobat being the most well-known \u2014  you actually don\u2019t need to download one to create a PDF from an existing paper document with your iPhone or iPad. You can just use Apple\u2019s Notes.</p>\n<h2 id=\"VzZohC\">Create a PDF ", "id": 815048, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/24191864/pdf-iphone-ipad-ios-how-to", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "How to create PDFs on iPhones using Notes", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-07-05T15:30:00+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Photo collage of a dilapidated Redbox kiosk.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/WcFikLgRoS6oBL0lU32mVyEyAUU=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73445